33
00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:29.580
So we're gonna talk about trust, and it's a concept.

34
00:04:29.580 --> 00:04:32.220
When I think about a concept, we can approach it in different ways.

35
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.020
We start with defining it.

36
00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:36.740
This is what I'm gonna do.

37
00:04:36.740 --> 00:04:40.320
Start with defining it, and then think about why does it even exist?

38
00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:41.580
Why bother?

39
00:04:41.580 --> 00:04:42.680
Why do we need it?

40
00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:44.020
Where does it come from?

41
00:04:44.020 --> 00:04:50.580
And then we can think about what causes it, and what does it cause, or what does it influence, and what influences it.

42
00:04:50.580 --> 00:04:58.600
I think one of the aspects we recovered was where we were trying to figure out, like, how does trust get transferred?

43
00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:18.140
And I was thinking, like, maybe you could just simply tell a person that you trust this person, but that does not quite work that way, because there's an inherent, what do you say, like, inherent idea of who other people are that you cannot necessarily transfer as easily as, say, money.

44
00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:21.740
Yeah, basically, I don't know if that was what you meant.

45
00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:27.060
What is underlying trust is the perception, basically.

46
00:05:27.060 --> 00:05:33.980
So the whole trust is a perception game, and that's what makes it tricky, because you have to perceive the perception of the other person.

47
00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:57.220
So if we go back to where the trust comes from, as we understand, we are the dominant species at the moment on Earth, and what we understand is the key factor that has helped us get to this point is the fact that we could cooperate in a larger scale.

48
00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:03.020
And the reason for that is that we could form an alliance.

49
00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:07.420
And is that, does it make sense?

50
00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:18.040
Yes, yes, like are you referring to, say, like the difference between the nomadic tribes as under transition towards the farming civilization?

51
00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:25.980
Even far before that, the effective alliance where you can actually act as a group.

52
00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:29.120
Did that arise from language?

53
00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:30.760
That can be a very important factor.

54
00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:39.360
So, yes, I believe that's very important to communicate that and create abstract concept that you can anchor on.

55
00:06:39.360 --> 00:07:02.280
So let's say when you look at a pack of wolves, for example, if they have their own mechanisms to establish trust or even other social creatures, we have the ability to leveraging our language and the ability to understand abstract concepts and make it visible to both of us.

56
00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:08.340
So both of us can actually understand we both share a certain value or both we belong to the certain group.

57
00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:20.860
The tribe, all this, the ability to perceive and comprehend abstract concepts and communicate that it allows and has allowed us to form alliance.

58
00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:26.940
And that is a very strong force.

59
00:07:27.100 --> 00:07:30.480
We will protect the tribe rather than ourselves.

60
00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:31.560
Yeah.

61
00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:35.280
I think that's the evolution of trust.

62
00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:36.060
Perfect, exactly.

63
00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:39.680
So, we're talking about the forces and the leverage.

64
00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:50.780
If you are just two or three, if you are 15 of you, and you can actually, all 15 of you can act as one entity, coordinate it, that's extremely powerful.

65
00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:54.200
This is, again, goes back to emergence that I was talking about.

66
00:07:54.200 --> 00:08:01.480
When in one layer, things are harmonic, they can create magnificent forces in the other layer.

67
00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:08.960
When a group of waves can create a tide, if they are in sync with each other, and in engineering, we learn about resonance, basically.

68
00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:15.060
When you sync up a few waves or a group of events, you can amplify the force.

69
00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:27.460
That's where the age for trust has come, because we have built institutes or mechanisms, layer on layer on layer, on this core, which is the alliance, which is the trust.

70
00:08:27.460 --> 00:08:31.580
And that's why we, that's why trust matters, and that's where the trust comes from.

71
00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:32.600
If you have anything to add.

72
00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:38.900
Yeah, it made me think, I think I was always busy looking up while you were talking, because I wanted to get the terminology right.

73
00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:55.400
There's a concept called Dunbar's Number, proposed by British anthropologist, Robin Dunbar, who basically thinks there's the optimum or maximum number of people you can form a stable social relationship with.

74
00:08:55.400 --> 00:09:02.620
And it's about 150 people, and that's a self-organizing, self-sustaining number.

75
00:09:02.620 --> 00:09:06.800
Beyond that, you need something to strengthen the trust.

76
00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:10.280
You need rules or evidence or something.

77
00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:22.620
But there is that number that humans, and they've had evidence to support it, that humans sort of self-organize into groups of about that number, between 100 and 250.

78
00:09:22.620 --> 00:09:31.880
And once you start getting beyond about 150, you need something besides the one-on-one relationship for the trust to still be there.

79
00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:33.180
You need rules.

80
00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:35.800
You need some evidence that backs up.

81
00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:41.360
This is why I should trust, because we put something in place that gives me a reason to trust.

82
00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:41.640
Yes.

83
00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:45.860
So you're referring to, in common terms, an abstraction.

84
00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:46.560
Yeah, yeah.

85
00:09:46.780 --> 00:10:05.500
It goes from, I know these people and I trust them, through to, okay, this is too big a group for me to know everyone, but we've abstracted the concept of trust, and there are some rules and evidence-based things that's saying, okay, if it conforms to this, I still trust this group of 500 people.

86
00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:06.420
Bigger tribe.

87
00:10:06.420 --> 00:10:09.260
Yeah, yeah, it's a bigger tribe, and we agreed on the rules.

88
00:10:09.260 --> 00:10:11.720
And yeah, the bigger it gets, the more rules you get.

89
00:10:11.720 --> 00:10:12.200
Yeah.

90
00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:14.300
And that's where we are today.

91
00:10:14.300 --> 00:10:15.560
That's exactly right.

92
00:10:15.560 --> 00:10:22.720
And that's where we have to substitute trust with some other mechanisms, basically to hold the organization together.

93
00:10:22.720 --> 00:10:29.520
And that's where my interest comes in, because I find trust one of the most powerful tools.

94
00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:31.340
If you think of a company, right?

95
00:10:31.340 --> 00:10:37.880
In a company, when employees come together, normally trust is not what is actually fundamentally holding it.

96
00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:40.320
It is the law.

97
00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:44.280
And Noam Chomsky has a very interesting take on this.

98
00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:49.000
It calls organizations later dictatorship bubbles.

99
00:10:49.000 --> 00:11:04.820
When you think about it, Noam Chomsky, yeah, describes organizations like a corporates, dictatorship bubbles, like a bubble of dictatorship, kind of in a membrane of an organization.

100
00:11:05.220 --> 00:11:08.640
And when you think about it, what if I interrupt?

101
00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:12.860
Do you refer to like bubble of dictatorship?

102
00:11:12.860 --> 00:11:19.740
Could that include like say a company itself being like an item of a society in some ways?

103
00:11:19.740 --> 00:11:28.740
And like you could say that, god damn, my boss is a dictator, or like my boss actually listens to his group and tries to form consensus.

104
00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:29.300
Is that?

105
00:11:29.300 --> 00:11:31.260
It's not necessarily a bad word in this case.

106
00:11:31.900 --> 00:11:33.260
I'm using it actually very loosely.

107
00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:48.700
But the way a group of people, let's say a hundred people in a company, who belong to the company, go over there and all their efforts are coordinated to deliver a result, is not a result of them trusting each other or necessarily.

108
00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:50.540
There are other forces that has replaced this.

109
00:11:50.540 --> 00:11:55.180
And what I'm arguing is those are artificial and arbitrary.

110
00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:58.500
And of course, there has been good reason for those things that exist.

111
00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:17.460
But if we can replace those things, if those relationships can be based on trust and the cooperation emerges from the relationship with amongst the people, the result would be much, much different and more harmonic internally and with the external organization.

112
00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:52.780
And you can also see this with teams of startups, for example, when they can sometimes work much harder with much less certainty around what they get, but what allows them to deliver this result, whereas a team with a manager is very hard time, the manager would have to get the same, even 10 percent of that result from a group of employees, is the fact that what brings them together is not enforced by laws or their need, that they know what they want and also they trust each other.

113
00:12:52.780 --> 00:13:01.400
That's where the word trust becomes a bit abstract because I see trust as the perception of the other person's perception.

114
00:13:01.400 --> 00:13:18.240
If three of us are working on the same group, I perceive your perception of what do you think about me, and the stronger I believe, you also believe that I'm also going to stick to this project, I'm going to back you, you would back me, and then that reinforces itself.

115
00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:22.340
That's why trust is a bidirectional phenomenon.

116
00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:37.280
I think it sort of takes advantage of the concept that a lot of the problems in the world is not a zero-sum game, and that if everybody contributes, then everybody actually gains more than what they put in as long as everybody contributes.

117
00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:52.780
And in some ways, that also reminds me of how people try to subvert the game's show where you actually try to backstab each other by saying, I'm going to definitely try to screw you over.

118
00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:55.540
I think, I can't remember what's the game's name, what it's called.

119
00:13:56.680 --> 00:13:57.620
There's one of them.

120
00:13:57.620 --> 00:13:58.240
Survival.

121
00:13:58.240 --> 00:13:58.980
Yes, yes, yes.

122
00:13:58.980 --> 00:14:16.020
So, the prisoner's dilemma is a very, very common university topic that is covered in psychology and I think it's very pertinent to what we're trying to speak here as well because it forms the basis that a lot of people already know and we could explain more about.

123
00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:16.460
Yeah.

124
00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:17.460
No, you're sure.

125
00:14:17.460 --> 00:14:18.160
Yeah, we can.

126
00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:21.200
Actually, anyone familiar with that prisoner's dilemma?

127
00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:24.740
The prisoner's dilemma.

128
00:14:24.740 --> 00:14:25.840
Now we're into psychology.

129
00:14:25.840 --> 00:14:29.820
We've moved on from reality shows to psychology.

130
00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:46.320
Talking about survivors, one where a group of people are put in an environment usually in Ireland and it's like now survive and form an alliance and because at a certain point you have to vote one person is getting kicked off and the last person wins a million dollars.

131
00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:58.140
So, you form alliances and people sometimes rightly trust their alliance and sometimes are completely fooled by someone in their alliance, who's just doing machinations behind the scene.

132
00:14:58.140 --> 00:15:05.800
And at a critical moment, they basically metaphorically stabbed someone in the back who thought they could trust them.

133
00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:12.820
And as Brian pointed out, it plays into a common sort of philosophical discussion called the Prisoner's Dilemma.

134
00:15:12.820 --> 00:15:13.820
Yeah.

135
00:15:13.820 --> 00:15:14.400
That's very interesting.

136
00:15:14.520 --> 00:15:22.280
I like since we were talking about the way organizations work, I had three use cases to discuss this topic.

137
00:15:22.280 --> 00:15:26.720
That was one of them, and I thought I'd bring it up now as we on it.

138
00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:36.980
One of the things that I noticed, it can be explored through the lens of trust is we work, we come together in terms of companies.

139
00:15:36.980 --> 00:15:51.780
When you think about like a standard work agreement where you come and you feel in a certain time and then that's how much you get paid, and the way everyone's kind of coordinated, our work is coordinated in companies.

140
00:15:51.780 --> 00:16:05.320
I trace it back to the whole design, even though it's not framed that way, even though you don't see it, I trace it to lack of trust, to the intention of people or to the desire of people.

141
00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:20.260
And I want to explain this more because this makes it very clear for me, a lot of issues that we already see in the workforce because we have moved in the whole entire workforce.

142
00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:27.000
The majority of it has moved from the type of work that we used to be doing when we put this structure in place.

143
00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:36.720
We're still keeping these structures and mechanisms and terminologies and rules, even though the nature of our work has changed and what we do.

144
00:16:36.720 --> 00:16:52.160
So the way I see it, the whole work structure is designed based on the assumption that when I go to work, I resent it, I don't like it, and any opportunity I get, I would choose it not to go to work.

145
00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:58.480
And every process is put in place to make sure I deliver enough for the business before I run away.

146
00:16:58.480 --> 00:17:05.300
I'm exaggerating a lot here, but you can trace this in all terminologies, the language, the rules.

147
00:17:05.300 --> 00:17:25.400
So this is a fundamental problem because we are undermining what can allow us to come together and to help us tap into our collective intelligence or collective potential with designing our workforce in an entirely different way based on the lack of trust.

148
00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:28.240
Andrew, what do you think about this observation?

149
00:17:28.240 --> 00:17:32.480
Because this is just an observation that I've had about the design of the way we work.

150
00:17:33.320 --> 00:17:48.620
Yeah, I mean, I think trust in a workplace is we collectivise action often because it's like if I act alone, I have to just trust everyone acts in my interest.

151
00:17:48.620 --> 00:17:56.200
But if I get everyone to work as a collective, then we have more power and I don't have to trust as much.

152
00:17:56.200 --> 00:18:05.580
Like, you know, bosses trust workers are going to do work and workers trust that bosses are going to give them decent conditions and decent remuneration.

153
00:18:06.720 --> 00:18:10.060
And in a significant number of cases, that all holds true.

154
00:18:10.060 --> 00:18:20.420
But yeah, then you get the case that when that trust breaks down, when someone breaks that trust, how much does the other party involved react?

155
00:18:21.860 --> 00:18:28.160
And, you know, do you still continue to cooperate and trust and go, well, maybe it'll be better next time?

156
00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:31.380
Or do you go for payback on the person that you feel broke your trust?

157
00:18:33.220 --> 00:18:53.720
And also, the other thing about the trust, that also it works here, because you see that there's a lot of process and elements to kind of respond to you when you are not acting trustworthy, in a trustworthy way, automatically it makes you not trusting back.

158
00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:56.620
And it makes you want basically to contribute less.

159
00:18:57.280 --> 00:19:05.980
And the more organization, the more the bigger the organization becomes, the more trust is substituted by more arbitrary and artificial forces.

160
00:19:05.980 --> 00:19:09.620
And that's where a lot of issues come from.

161
00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:17.320
That's the reason I'm very interested in this particular topic, is that there are alternative ways to coordinate workforce.

162
00:19:17.320 --> 00:19:18.280
Hi, this is your host.

163
00:19:18.280 --> 00:19:20.800
I hope you're enjoying the talk so far.

164
00:19:20.800 --> 00:19:24.080
Some of the interesting corporate structures out there are corruptives.

165
00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:32.260
And as luck would have it, we have Anthony Magmulley in the audience, who is an expert when it comes to corruptives, as we will find out soon enough.

166
00:19:33.520 --> 00:19:35.560
I suppose when you have...

167
00:19:35.560 --> 00:19:37.760
There's two forms of employee ownership.

168
00:19:37.760 --> 00:19:39.080
So there's a...

169
00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:48.660
You can be in a company where they have broad-based employee ownership, so usually through shares.

170
00:19:49.900 --> 00:19:55.640
And often that acts as a real incentive for people because they haven't just got a sense of ownership.

171
00:19:55.640 --> 00:20:00.640
They do actually have an ownership stake in the business that they're working in.

172
00:20:00.640 --> 00:20:02.580
So that's sort of one level.

173
00:20:02.580 --> 00:20:07.220
And then with worker cooperatives, this is sort of the spectrum.

174
00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:19.560
With worker cooperatives, you generally have that ownership stake, but you also have a set of principles that are around people working together democratically.

175
00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:26.880
So then you have to figure out those sorts of issues that you mentioned before about the dumb bars or one of those sorts of things, you know.

176
00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:32.880
Because you can't have everyone in the room making decisions for absolutely everything all the time.

177
00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:40.880
So how do you actually structure teams and groups and people to have responsibility and then being democratically accountable?

178
00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:51.760
So I suppose one of the key things that interests me is the relationship between shared ownership and democracy.

179
00:20:51.760 --> 00:21:05.600
You know, because you could have a regular company that has a regular ownership structure by external shareholders with the board, the CEO having an actual ownership, the state having its shares and the rest don't.

180
00:21:05.600 --> 00:21:19.160
You can have democracy within that, but if you don't match the democracy with the ownership, like that to me presents some problems.

181
00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:23.620
So that's where economic democracy, I think, comes into it.

182
00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:26.940
Not just formal democracy.

183
00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:32.560
When you're talking about the governance, right, when you talk about democracy, the governance aspect of the organization.

184
00:21:32.960 --> 00:21:33.980
Yeah, there's the governance.

185
00:21:33.980 --> 00:21:38.780
So you could have a regular company, though, where everyone has more of a say.

186
00:21:38.780 --> 00:21:54.220
But if you've still got a small group of owners, and most of the owners who are external to the business have nothing to do with the business, don't work in the business, their interests are to that this business is as profitable as possible, so they get a return on their investment.

187
00:21:54.220 --> 00:21:58.860
Whereas in a worker cooperative, generally speaking, it flips it.

188
00:21:58.860 --> 00:22:04.360
So the people who are working in the business have an ownership stake in the business.

189
00:22:04.360 --> 00:22:20.800
And so they want to be able to work together, make decisions together, but they also know that, for example, if there's a profit share arrangement that's equitable, if this company goes really well, we're going to all do well on an equitable basis.

190
00:22:20.800 --> 00:22:38.040
So I think the sort of the, like, we sometimes move democracy, we kind of think of it as something apart from things like ownership rights, whereas I think we need to think about those two things in tandem.

191
00:22:38.040 --> 00:22:40.140
That's what interests me about working for one reason.

192
00:22:40.140 --> 00:22:43.400
There's some good examples of them globally, but it's not a widespread thing.

193
00:22:43.900 --> 00:22:47.800
Well, that's the approach that we're taking within our democracy, actually.

194
00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:49.660
We're going to have the working court.

195
00:22:49.660 --> 00:23:05.060
So the idea is that every, technically speaking, every single person in the plan would potentially have an equal financial share, one share only non-saleable, so it's not volatile in that sense.

196
00:23:05.060 --> 00:23:13.400
But take that true democratic approach where we've all got equal say, where we've all got equal financial responsibility involved.

197
00:23:15.020 --> 00:23:26.620
As you were saying before, when you've got a board of directors, that potentially undermines the democratic system that you may have sitting within the organisation itself.

198
00:23:26.620 --> 00:23:27.460
Yeah.

199
00:23:27.460 --> 00:23:29.120
So essentially, it's all third-carrying.

200
00:23:29.340 --> 00:23:29.780
Yeah.

201
00:23:29.780 --> 00:23:36.000
In a workers' cooperative, the members' workers will elect the board.

202
00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:40.620
The issue you have, though, if you just have one share per person, it's not transferable.

203
00:23:42.820 --> 00:23:46.080
And you do have that within co-ops as well, but you can...

204
00:23:46.080 --> 00:23:51.580
Someone could get more, purchase more shares, and you can have some...

205
00:23:51.580 --> 00:23:59.200
Like, you've got investment in a business or an enterprise is always a tricky thing, and that's a real issue for the co-op movement as well.

206
00:23:59.200 --> 00:24:02.460
So, I hope that helps the conversation that you're having at the front.

207
00:24:02.460 --> 00:24:11.960
Sorry, can I just ask you, so are there co-ops in Australia, or somewhere where some members have more shares than others?

208
00:24:11.960 --> 00:24:19.740
Yeah, so, I mean, look, I'm a bit techy with this stuff, but in a co-op structure, you can't have more than 20%.

209
00:24:20.540 --> 00:24:31.060
No individual member can have more than 20% of the issued share capital, but the thing with a co-op is that no matter what, it's one member, one vote.

210
00:24:31.060 --> 00:24:42.860
The difference between a co-op and a company is that the more shares that you own in a company, generally speaking, the more votes that you have.

211
00:24:43.960 --> 00:24:50.620
So it's really more of a device, within a corporate, generally speaking, is investment from the people that work there.

212
00:24:50.620 --> 00:25:04.740
If they've invested more, then in proportion to the effort that they've made, the value that they've created, on an equitable, agreed basis, they may get some extra financial compensation.

213
00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:11.260
And a business does need investment, and often it's gonna need external investors as well, which is a real challenge for co-ops.

214
00:25:11.260 --> 00:25:17.920
Because you wanna keep the external investors away from the decision-making process.

215
00:25:17.920 --> 00:25:18.960
So anyway.

216
00:25:18.960 --> 00:25:29.020
I hope Anthony McMillan's explanation about co-opters was enlightening, as well as the complexity that comes in terms of maintaining its own integrity.

217
00:25:30.140 --> 00:25:40.580
We then switched topics from co-opters towards how do parties maintain their own integrity, especially political parties.

218
00:25:40.580 --> 00:25:48.320
So one of the things we were talking about was especially about this event called the American Southern Strategy.

219
00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:55.680
That also reminds me of what makes a party a party.

220
00:25:55.680 --> 00:26:04.360
If somebody goes into floods, a particular party with their own members and essentially takes over, then is that really the same party?

221
00:26:04.360 --> 00:26:10.740
The key things I would mention in terms of the event is in America, there's this thing called the Southern Strategy.

222
00:26:10.880 --> 00:26:20.300
If I remembered where all the great big swap, where the parties of the Republicans and the Democrats essentially swapped ideology.

223
00:26:20.320 --> 00:26:22.960
And it's really weird.

224
00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:25.300
I'm not sure how to elaborate on it.

225
00:26:25.300 --> 00:26:29.500
Broadly, like civil war, the Southern States were Democrat.

226
00:26:29.500 --> 00:26:33.100
They, Lincoln was a Republican.

227
00:26:33.100 --> 00:26:37.120
The Republicans were the Northern elite, the intelligentsia.

228
00:26:37.420 --> 00:26:41.280
The working class South were Democrat, racist as hell.

229
00:26:41.280 --> 00:26:46.160
The North was racist as hell too, but they kind of started to draw the line at actual slavery.

230
00:26:46.160 --> 00:26:50.260
And so that was until the 20th century.

231
00:26:50.260 --> 00:26:58.640
And Democrat policy started to shift more towards progressive social justice things.

232
00:26:58.640 --> 00:27:01.120
And the Republicans saw themselves losing power.

233
00:27:01.120 --> 00:27:02.220
And they went, hey, you know what?

234
00:27:02.220 --> 00:27:04.920
There's a bunch of angry white people in the South.

235
00:27:05.840 --> 00:27:13.800
If we went down and panned it to them, we'd win all these previously Democrat states.

236
00:27:13.820 --> 00:27:15.860
And it worked.

237
00:27:15.860 --> 00:27:25.360
And in fact, the president, Lyndon Johnson, when he signed the Civil Rights Act, he was reported to have said, that's it, we've lost the South for two generations.

238
00:27:26.960 --> 00:27:36.240
He did it because it was the right thing to do, but he said, that Republican Southern strategy is going to kick into high gear now, and it will take us ages to make the ground back.

239
00:27:36.240 --> 00:27:38.320
But yeah, it is literally weird.

240
00:27:38.320 --> 00:27:44.680
At one point, Democrats were the South, and were very popular with the racists.

241
00:27:44.680 --> 00:27:48.580
The Republicans were the North, and were most against slavery.

242
00:27:48.580 --> 00:27:52.560
Somewhere in the 20th century, it just went, and it's swapped.

243
00:27:52.600 --> 00:27:55.240
You're quite knowledgeable about the Republican Party.

244
00:27:55.240 --> 00:27:59.240
Yeah, so you're quite knowledgeable about the US and the Republican Party.

245
00:27:59.240 --> 00:28:01.140
I'm a little bit obsessive about it, yes.

246
00:28:01.140 --> 00:28:04.400
Because I'm the oldest person here.

247
00:28:05.540 --> 00:28:16.160
And so I do know that maybe 20 or 30 years ago, there was at least a small group of people within the Republican Party who were quite left-wing.

248
00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:17.040
Are they still there?

249
00:28:17.720 --> 00:28:22.260
Well, there are certainly people in the US.

250
00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:29.060
Republican Party who I would regard as thoroughly decent people and care about those less well off than them.

251
00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:32.740
And you could argue they're progressive on a number of things.

252
00:28:32.740 --> 00:28:37.360
They just probably are economically a bit conservative.

253
00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:42.500
They don't agree with massive welfare programs, necessarily or not.

254
00:28:42.500 --> 00:28:45.920
They're just not dictating policy and haven't for a couple of decades now.

255
00:28:46.760 --> 00:28:49.880
I think the group that I'm thinking on is probably just at the end.

256
00:28:50.220 --> 00:28:54.000
I think there's definitely reasonable people in the Republican Party.

257
00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:56.800
I'm talking about people who are quite strongly at that point.

258
00:28:56.800 --> 00:29:03.820
Well, look, for instance, one of the Democratic presidential nominees, Elizabeth Warren, started off as a Republican.

259
00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:13.140
She thought she believed Republican ideology more, but as they shifted further and further to reactionary policy, she just went, I'm not on board with this anymore.

260
00:29:13.260 --> 00:29:15.700
And she actually fit to the Democratic Party.

261
00:29:18.320 --> 00:29:32.700
I suppose in our own country, we could reflect on the history of the White Australia Policy and how that was not always a so-called right-wing conservative cause.

262
00:29:32.700 --> 00:29:53.640
There's very deep relationship between the labour movement and protectionism, and some of that kind of economically-driven policy in that area, which just makes the whole thing very interesting and complex.

263
00:29:53.640 --> 00:30:00.140
But it's also back to your point, sort of around the tribalism stuff, you know?

264
00:30:00.140 --> 00:30:10.720
Like I was reflecting today, I saw a Twitter thing where some racist people were tweeting out about a fire at one of the stations, one of the train stations.

265
00:30:10.720 --> 00:30:18.820
And all the comments were, well, of course, they're those lovely African people and really horrible kind of comments.

266
00:30:18.820 --> 00:30:23.460
You sort of wonder, you know, what's the tribal things that is?

267
00:30:23.460 --> 00:30:26.360
Because there's this good tribal trust thing.

268
00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:30.560
And then there's this other thing where they're kind of different from us.

269
00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:32.520
Yeah.

270
00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:34.480
I love it.

271
00:30:34.480 --> 00:30:35.300
You love tribalism?

272
00:30:35.360 --> 00:30:55.260
No, I love it when there's, I think the term is cognitive dissonance, when people get an acute sharp moment in their understanding, their beliefs, which is flipped, yeah, flipped upside down in an instant.

273
00:30:55.260 --> 00:31:10.040
And you can actually, I watched Lee Sayles one time when she was interviewing a liberal party politician discussing immigration.

274
00:31:10.060 --> 00:31:27.560
And the current discourse was that anyone who was against immigration is a racist, or wants lower levels of immigration is a racist.

275
00:31:27.760 --> 00:31:43.440
And you could see, and I forget who her guest was, which politician, but he very eloquently phrased his arguments in different terms.

276
00:31:43.440 --> 00:31:55.080
And you could see that moment where she went, fuck, it's like, and her whole world, as she knew it, was flipped in that millisecond.

277
00:31:55.180 --> 00:32:09.500
And it's fascinating how it can, what you were saying before about racism and the blacks getting votes.

278
00:32:09.500 --> 00:32:28.200
I'll bet you there were millions of people around Australia who had their moment, their split, their awakening moment, which is, you know, when they realized that, oh, blacks weren't lazy, violent drunks, that they actually had a brain.

279
00:32:28.220 --> 00:32:44.220
And, you know, and then I find that, you know, that's profound and, you know, we've sort of gone off on a tangent here, talking about conceptualizing and philosophy in a way.

280
00:32:44.220 --> 00:32:52.820
But, you know, that's really, like getting to the heart of the polarity in US politics.

281
00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:59.380
And you were talking about there are Republicans that are very left-leaning, broadly.

282
00:32:59.380 --> 00:33:06.180
Yeah, I mean, you get those moments, and politicians flipping sides.

283
00:33:06.180 --> 00:33:11.060
But, you know, we need to remove sides.

284
00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:13.920
Like, sides are stupid.

285
00:33:13.920 --> 00:33:14.640
They really are.

286
00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:45.620
Like, but calling yourself left or right is so ludicrous, because there are a million issues that make up someone's reference, and who they are, and you could get a so-called lefty and a so-called righty agreeing on ten things out of fifty, that they were, you know, but it's all maybe on five hundred things out of ten thousand things.

287
00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:47.340
It's much more complex than that.

288
00:33:47.340 --> 00:33:50.260
You're calling yourself a lefty or a righty.

289
00:33:52.060 --> 00:33:57.040
This is, this gets into topic of identity, group identities.

290
00:33:57.040 --> 00:33:57.980
So it's not that easy.

291
00:33:57.980 --> 00:33:59.260
Tribalism and tribalism.

292
00:33:59.300 --> 00:34:15.860
Yeah, but it's not, it's a very, it's also a natural thing because we, to form alliance and to be able to act as a bigger group of people, to have influence, you need to be able to identify as a group.

293
00:34:15.860 --> 00:34:18.739
You need anchors, you need words.

294
00:34:18.739 --> 00:34:23.360
You need to be able to, in the past, traditions or religions would serve that purpose.

295
00:34:23.360 --> 00:34:24.360
So you would say, I'm Jewish.

296
00:34:24.360 --> 00:34:25.480
You're Jewish, that's it.

297
00:34:25.480 --> 00:34:26.600
So I know I can back you.

298
00:34:26.600 --> 00:34:40.139
I know what kind of things you are, what kind of, I mean, as an entity, what kind of, I can build my perceptions about your values, your reactions, interactions, and what I can expect happens.

299
00:34:40.139 --> 00:34:42.300
It's reliable, right?

300
00:34:43.480 --> 00:34:56.940
So as we're losing that, we are subconsciously, I believe, in this society, we're trying to find those identities that we can grasp on, right?

301
00:34:57.080 --> 00:34:59.160
And identify as.

302
00:34:59.160 --> 00:35:08.940
And that's true, if we could all talk about complex topics all the time, that would be perfect, but it's not how things actually happen.

303
00:35:08.940 --> 00:35:10.660
This is the challenge, I would say.

304
00:35:10.660 --> 00:35:11.940
This is the challenge, because...

305
00:35:11.940 --> 00:35:27.780
Social media, I believe, and technology, and the information age, I believe, has played a big part in the shift towards polarizing in belief.

306
00:35:27.780 --> 00:35:32.920
And you're saying that we've...

307
00:35:32.920 --> 00:35:44.020
I totally agree with you that we're floundering, and people in the information age are looking for a new structure, but they haven't realized it yet.

308
00:35:45.960 --> 00:35:55.900
I'm not suggesting, looking from outside, what I'm seeing is that people would need to identify as a group, and this is their way by leveraging on words.

309
00:35:55.900 --> 00:35:57.540
And then it's flawed, right?

310
00:35:58.500 --> 00:36:02.420
And this is where the actual issues come from.

311
00:36:02.420 --> 00:36:10.660
When we were talking about Republicans, it just was very interestingly related, you know, as like the whole impeachment is happening.

312
00:36:11.300 --> 00:36:17.000
The fact that Republicans have managed to stay united, right, regardless of what the topic is, right?

313
00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:23.440
They're around one thing, that we're all Republicans, we're gonna stick together, regardless of what the argument is, right?

314
00:36:23.440 --> 00:36:25.020
That's their approach.

315
00:36:25.020 --> 00:36:28.320
And this is what I'm talking about.

316
00:36:29.100 --> 00:36:41.080
This is now, again, trust is playing out because they all need to trust the fact that none of them is gonna kind of split, because at any point, the whole thing may collapse.

317
00:36:41.080 --> 00:36:43.560
And the sooner you leave the camp, the better it is.

318
00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:54.840
But if all of you trust each other, you can actually stick and fight back, regardless of the arguments, and regardless of how bad the evidence is against you.

319
00:36:54.840 --> 00:37:00.900
So can I ask you, do you think that the Republicans have trust in each other?

320
00:37:01.200 --> 00:37:02.660
I'm just looking from outside.

321
00:37:02.660 --> 00:37:04.600
I think they don't trust each other.

322
00:37:04.600 --> 00:37:12.960
When I see there is no vote from Republicans, zero vote from Republicans, to me, it means and there is no argument again.

323
00:37:12.960 --> 00:37:15.340
Yeah, it's very, very cohesive, basically.

324
00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:17.120
This is what I see.

325
00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:37.980
And I'm not suggesting it's good or bad, but what I'm seeing, the group dynamic that I'm observing, relating it back to this topic, that it's also, I also want to relate this to other situations where there's a perception, the whole trust is perception, I think we all agree on this.

326
00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:42.240
The perception starts breaking, and all of a sudden the whole thing flips.

327
00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:45.680
This can also happen here, and we probably may see it.

328
00:37:45.680 --> 00:38:20.560
An example that I remember was when in the financial market around 10 years ago, when there was a rumor about Greece getting loaned from the EU, which wasn't true, but that caused the whole euro to fall very badly because of the rumor, because that was an example where the whole alliances were built on some fundamental assumptions or perception that when that gets shattered, then everything starts collapsing.

329
00:38:20.560 --> 00:38:24.500
And with this left and right, we also see that.

330
00:38:24.500 --> 00:38:30.060
And the trouble with that is the recovery is not that easy.

331
00:38:30.060 --> 00:38:42.160
So once a concept like left or right gets, once you have always been kind of identifying as a group, and then when you lose it, it's not easy to just go to a different camp.

332
00:38:42.160 --> 00:38:48.760
I'm not too sure if this is relevant directly to the point, but it reminds me of Penny Rong.

333
00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:54.740
And the fact that, you know, Penny Rong is known as being a pro-LGBT.

334
00:38:55.500 --> 00:39:08.920
But like when she was in politics at that time, before the gay marriage debate, like she was pretty much saying that she was following the Labour Party line of no gay marriage.

335
00:39:08.920 --> 00:39:19.320
And I think during a Q&amp;A session, there were one of the person was saying, we know you're not this person, like Labour knows you're not this person and et cetera.

336
00:39:19.320 --> 00:39:20.540
So what's going on here?

337
00:39:21.180 --> 00:39:30.740
And so there's this aspects of a party is not really a one dimensional kind of ideology, but actually made up of lots of different kind of ideology.

338
00:39:30.740 --> 00:39:41.120
But then this need of presenting a unity, because otherwise other party may try to attack you and break the trust in that sense.

339
00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:42.200
So is that important?

340
00:39:42.500 --> 00:39:44.760
I would say what I, cause people often bring that up.

341
00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:47.200
They say ridiculous things about Penny Wong.

342
00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:49.640
She's a lesbian and the same.

343
00:39:49.640 --> 00:39:54.220
She was anti LGBT rights because she towed the party line.

344
00:39:54.220 --> 00:39:58.280
What I honestly think was happening there, that's when Julia Gillard was prime minister.

345
00:39:58.280 --> 00:40:02.240
She was under attack on a hundred different fronts.

346
00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:03.940
Most of them quite unreasonable.

347
00:40:03.940 --> 00:40:05.780
Some of them were probably quite reasonable.

348
00:40:05.780 --> 00:40:11.360
And there was the bubbling up of, should we be pushing for marriage equality?

349
00:40:11.360 --> 00:40:14.320
I honestly, and Julia Gillard was an atheist.

350
00:40:14.680 --> 00:40:18.700
Julia Gillard has no objection to gay people or gay marriage.

351
00:40:18.700 --> 00:40:19.840
She just doesn't.

352
00:40:19.840 --> 00:40:26.460
But I honestly believe she just pulled Penny Wong into a room and said, I can't have another cultural battle.

353
00:40:26.460 --> 00:40:27.440
It'll destroy us.

354
00:40:27.440 --> 00:40:29.100
I'm barely holding on.

355
00:40:29.100 --> 00:40:30.820
I've got a minority government.

356
00:40:30.820 --> 00:40:32.440
I just can't do it.

357
00:40:32.440 --> 00:40:37.840
I need you to basically support policy that says you're less than human.

358
00:40:37.840 --> 00:40:45.820
And Penny Wong, my god, she must be the most loyal person on the planet, because she said, I'll support the party line.

359
00:40:46.420 --> 00:40:47.640
I think it's obvious.

360
00:40:47.640 --> 00:40:53.260
It's the opposite of what she wanted, but it was just a really harsh political environment.

361
00:40:53.260 --> 00:40:59.220
And she put party needs above her own, which is wild, but she did.

362
00:40:59.740 --> 00:41:01.320
Why is it a strange thing?

363
00:41:02.980 --> 00:41:05.580
Because it's just a matter of timing.

364
00:41:10.260 --> 00:41:13.300
Gay and lesbian marriage was coming.

365
00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:14.660
It was just a matter of time.

366
00:41:14.760 --> 00:41:28.020
True, but it put, for many years, put Penny Wong in the position of having to repeatedly say, I support a policy that by definition regards me as less than other people.

367
00:41:28.020 --> 00:41:29.660
And she never blinked.

368
00:41:29.660 --> 00:41:39.140
That's a degree of loyalty that I, I, I, whoa, it's just literally that the policy that say you don't have the right to do this.

369
00:41:39.140 --> 00:41:41.880
It's saying you deserve less human rights than other people.

370
00:41:41.880 --> 00:41:44.120
That's pure, pure tribalism.

371
00:41:44.120 --> 00:41:45.680
Yeah, that's hardcore.

372
00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:49.760
I am going with the tribe over my own short-term needs.

373
00:41:49.760 --> 00:41:51.760
And that, that was amazing.

374
00:41:52.480 --> 00:41:53.780
I don't think it's the sort of thing I can do.

375
00:41:53.780 --> 00:42:02.520
That's a really interesting thing here, because like I think initially the tone of our conversation initially was that tribalism is bad.

376
00:42:02.520 --> 00:42:11.240
Well, yeah, it's, as you say, I think in almost any system, the good points and the bad points are the same thing.

377
00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:12.700
It just depends how they go.

378
00:42:12.700 --> 00:42:15.580
A tribe is loyal to each other.

379
00:42:15.580 --> 00:42:16.860
That is good.

380
00:42:16.860 --> 00:42:25.220
A tribe can end up being loyal to each other in a way that flies in the face of logic or decency that is bad.

381
00:42:25.220 --> 00:42:28.860
I looked something up because I wanted to get it right because it was reasonably complicated.

382
00:42:28.860 --> 00:42:31.760
And someone talked about it.

383
00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:33.060
And they're talking about America.

384
00:42:33.060 --> 00:42:39.220
They're an American talking about the rise of tribal epistemology and epistemology is a branch.

385
00:42:39.220 --> 00:42:40.760
We're back into philosophy.

386
00:42:42.120 --> 00:42:48.720
It has to do with knowing reality, coming to know reality and accepting things as true and reality.

387
00:42:49.360 --> 00:43:05.700
And what this person is saying that their view, tribal epistemology is when the tribal bond rejects actual epistemological principles.

388
00:43:05.700 --> 00:43:11.620
In fact, you stop trying to find an objective truth because it could weaken the tribe.

